<DOC><DOCNO> AP881222-0058 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-12-22-88 0646EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a PM-WeatherpageWeather     12-22 0542</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Weatherpage Weather,0559</SECOND><HEAD>Heavy Snow In The West</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Snowstorms moved from the Pacific coast across the mountains ofthe West today as the rest of the nation enjoyed relatively tranquilweather.   A cold front crossing the Rockies today brought 5 to 20 inches ofsnow to California's Sierra Nevada. A second storm was expected toproduce heavy snow today and a third may bring more heavy snow thisweekend.   Winter storm warnings were in effect for California's MountShasta, Siskiyou Mountains and northern Sierra Nevada, where 12 to18 inches of snow were possible, and for higher elevations ofsouthwestern Oregon.   A winter storm watch was issued for the southern Sierra Nevadaand for higher elevations of the Lake Tahoe area of Nevada.   Snow advisories were in effect for California's northwestmountains, south-central Oregon and parts of Idaho.   A high surf advisory was posted for the northern coast ofCalifornia, where large ocean swells and high tides were expected tocause dangerous surf conditions the next several days. A galewarning was in effect for Oregon's coast.   Snow also fell in sections of Utah, Wyoming and Colorado.   In Utah, the heavy snow caused hundreds of accidents, but noserious injuries were reported. Salt Lake City police logged 117accident reports in 10 hours Wednesday.   Clouds were over much of the nation east of the Rockies, with fogin the Southeast. Showers and thunderstorms fell over extremesouthern Florida and rain showers developing along a cold frontmoved off the mid-Atlantic Coast.   Gale warnings were in effect for lakes Erie and Huron tonight.   Today's forecast called for snow from the eastern Dakotas andeastern Nebraska to much of the upper Mississippi Valley, northernWisconsin and Upper Michigan; rain showers from southeast Minnesotaand southern Wisconsin to the Mississippi and western lower Ohiovalleys; showers and thunderstorms in the lower Mississippi Valley;and widespread rain along the Pacific Coast.   High temperatures were predicted in the 30s or 40s across much ofthe nation; 20s in parts of eastern Idaho, western Montana, westernWyoming, North Dakota, northern Minnesota, Upper Michigan, andcentral New England; 50s and 60s from the central California coastto the southern Plains, Tennessee Valley and the southern AtlanticCoast states; 70s in the Gulf Coast; and 80s in the southern half ofFlorida.   Temperatures around the nation at 2 a.m. EST ranged from 9degrees at Limestone, Maine, and Sault Ste. Marie, Mich., to 71degrees at Fort Lauderdale, Fla.   Other reports:   _East: Atlanta 49 foggy; Boston 38 fair; Buffalo 29 snow;Charleston, S.C. 57 fair; Cincinnati 32 foggy; Detroit 30 partlycloudy; Miami 69 partly cloudy; New York 37 fair; Philadelphia 36fair; Pittsburgh 31 cloudy; Portland, Maine 32 fair; Washington 39fair.   _Central: Bismarck 33 cloudy; Chicago 33 fair; Dallas-Fort Worth64 cloudy; Denver 37 fair; Des Moines 30 partly cloudy; Indianapolis30 fair; Kansas City 41 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 29 cloudy;Nashville 48 foggy; New Orleans 62 foggy; St. Louis 34 fair.   _West: Albuquerque 37 fair; Anchorage 14 cloudy; Las Vegas 40fair; Los Angeles 53 fair; Phoenix 46 fair; Salt Lake City 28cloudy; San Diego 51 fair; San Francisco 49 cloudy; Seattle 37cloudy.   _Canada: Montreal 12 fair; Toronto 21 fair.</TEXT></DOC>